{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728165520,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_3eLcs5s72rwvxHrWwflGXYpj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"memory\\.embedded|memory\\.enriched|EMBEDDED|ENRICHED|register_pipeline_consumers","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api","include":"*.py"},"output":"Found 15 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:\n  Line 1653:     enrichment fields back. The worker also emits ``ENRICHED`` after\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:\n  Line 186:         # A4 #14 — back-channel idempotency. Both the ENRICHED and\n\n  Line 187:         # EMBEDDED handlers fire ``detect_contradictions_async`` for\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:\n  Line 736:     contradiction detection, the CAURA-595 ENRICHED consumer) — see\n\n  Line 749:     (the request session has closed), the CAURA-595 ``ENRICHED``\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/app.py:\n  Line 395:             register_pipeline_consumers,\n\n  Line 400:         register_pipeline_consumers(lifecycle_adapter)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/config.py:\n  Line 69:     #   the LLM fields re-fetch after the back-channel ``ENRICHED``\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py:\n  Line 6: * ``Topics.Memory.ENRICHED`` (CAURA-595) — fired after a successful\n\n  Line 8: * ``Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED`` (loadtest-7 fix) — fired after a\n\n  Line 45:     \"\"\"Process one ``Topics.Memory.ENRICHED`` event.\n\n  Line 136:     \"\"\"Process one ``Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED`` event.\n\n  Line 225:     bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.ENRICHED, handle_memory_enriched)\n\n  Line 226:     bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED, handle_memory_embedded)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/schedule_background_tasks.py:\n  Line 94:             # fires via the ``EMBEDDED`` back-channel after ``core-worker``\n","metadata":{"matches":15,"truncated":false},"title":"memory\\.embedded|memory\\.enriched|EMBEDDED|ENRICHED|register_pipeline_consumers","time":{"start":1780728165502,"end":1780728165520}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02c080efe7841890016a23c1656580819183f5e63af21a9f9b"}},"id":"prt_e9bab747b001mGougoROzF2Rdj","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","messageID":"msg_e9bab52b0001YKLEiTa3uRndZI"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780728165799,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab75a5001TpHPDuiTqcrSlp","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"9f725f18d182447363ecc0b9c7f577e068072131","messageID":"msg_e9bab52b0001YKLEiTa3uRndZI","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":94648,"input":6254,"output":284,"reasoning":46,"cache":{"write":0,"read":88064}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780728168149,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab7ed4001X6nQaxragtgIxg","messageID":"msg_e9bab76bb001bokvLlWaHWPb4S","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","snapshot":"78649f6e74ee34f1ef7cae7d6347e7fb7460bf0b","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780728175125,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab875b001h3ihvvBSQDZae6","messageID":"msg_e9bab76bb001bokvLlWaHWPb4S","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","type":"text","text":"The write path uses pending metadata plus later PATCHes to converge row state; it also has a NULL-embedding backfill that republishes the same embed-request events rather than inventing a separate repair path.","time":{"start":1780728170331,"end":1780728175124},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0317272579d6221c016a23c16a4b588191910891f81d006e21","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728175221,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_INrhhD4mwP0499H7eM39zOUd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py","offset":1,"limit":250},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Pub/Sub consumer for core-api.\n2: \n3: Subscribes core-api to two back-channels published by core-worker\n4: after the async write path lands a memory row:\n5: \n6: * ``Topics.Memory.ENRICHED`` (CAURA-595) — fired after a successful\n7:   enrichment PATCH.\n8: * ``Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED`` (loadtest-7 fix) — fired after a\n9:   successful embedding PATCH.\n10: \n11: Both consumers run :func:`detect_contradictions_async`. Two events\n12: trigger the detector because either the embed or the enrich worker\n13: can land first, and the detector needs both fields available; whichever\n14: event arrives second sees the other side present and runs detection.\n15: The detector is idempotent under repeated calls on the same row, so\n16: the rare case where both events trigger detection back-to-back doesn't\n17: double-write contradiction rows.\n18: \n19: Atomic-fact fan-out (parent → child memories) is intentionally not\n20: handled here. The worker drops ``EnrichmentResult.atomic_facts``\n21: entirely (see ``_ENRICHMENT_UNROUTED_FIELDS`` in\n22: ``core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py``), so they never reach\n23: storage. Persisting them at the worker side and fanning out from a\n24: storage fetch is a separate piece of work.\n25: \"\"\"\n26: \n27: from __future__ import annotations\n28: \n29: import logging\n30: \n31: from pydantic import ValidationError\n32: \n33: from common.events.base import Event\n34: from common.events.factory import get_event_bus\n35: from common.events.memory_embedded import MemoryEmbedded\n36: from common.events.memory_enriched import MemoryEnriched\n37: from common.events.topics import Topics\n38: from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n39: from core_api.services.contradiction_detector import detect_contradictions_async\n40: \n41: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n42: \n43: \n44: async def handle_memory_enriched(event: Event) -> None:\n45:     \"\"\"Process one ``Topics.Memory.ENRICHED`` event.\n46: \n47:     Loads the memory row from storage (so we have the embedding +\n48:     fleet_id that the minimal payload doesn't carry) and dispatches to\n49:     ``detect_contradictions_async`` when the embedding has already\n50:     landed. Schema-drift / malformed payloads ack-drop with a loud\n51:     ``dropped=True`` log entry so a poison message can't loop the\n52:     subscription.\n53: \n54:     The detection coroutine is awaited inline rather than spawned via\n55:     ``track_task``: it owns its own ``try/except`` and never raises, so\n56:     the bus always acks regardless of detection outcome — but the await\n57:     delays the ack until detection completes, which prevents\n58:     redelivery from stacking concurrent detections on the same memory.\n59:     \"\"\"\n60:     try:\n61:         payload = MemoryEnriched(**event.payload)\n62:     except (ValidationError, TypeError):\n63:         # ``ValidationError`` covers shape drift (missing required\n64:         # fields, wrong types). ``TypeError`` covers ``event.payload``\n65:         # not being a mapping at all — ``**non_dict`` raises before\n66:         # Pydantic ever sees it. Both are poison-message conditions\n67:         # that re-raising would just nack-loop on; ack-drop loudly.\n68:         logger.exception(\n69:             \"dropping malformed memory-enriched payload\",\n70:             extra={\n71:                 \"event_type\": event.event_type,\n72:                 \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n73:                 \"dropped\": True,\n74:             },\n75:         )\n76:         return\n77: \n78:     sc = get_storage_client()\n79:     memory = await sc.get_memory(str(payload.memory_id))\n80:     if memory is None:\n81:         # Row was deleted between the worker's PATCH and our handler\n82:         # picking up the event. Common-enough race to ack-drop without\n83:         # noise; matches the worker's 404 handling.\n84:         logger.info(\n85:             \"memory-enriched: target row missing; ack-dropping\",\n86:             extra={\n87:                 \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n88:                 \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n89:             },\n90:         )\n91:         return\n92: \n93:     embedding = memory.get(\"embedding\")\n94:     if not embedding:\n95:         # Embed worker hasn't completed yet (or its PATCH 404'd).\n96:         # ``deferred_reason`` is structured so a Cloud Logging metric\n97:         # can scrape the count of skipped detections — without it,\n98:         # there's no production visibility into how often the race\n99:         # fires.\n100:         logger.info(\n101:             \"memory-enriched: embedding not yet present; deferring contradiction detection\",\n102:             extra={\n103:                 \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n104:                 \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n105:                 \"deferred_reason\": \"embedding_missing\",\n106:             },\n107:         )\n108:         return\n109: \n110:     fleet_id = memory.get(\"fleet_id\")\n111: \n112:     # Pass the already-fetched row through so the detector skips a\n113:     # redundant ``sc.get_memory`` (it still re-checks ``deleted_at``\n114:     # for the soft-delete-during-detection race).\n115:     await detect_contradictions_async(\n116:         payload.memory_id,\n117:         payload.tenant_id,\n118:         fleet_id,\n119:         payload.content,\n120:         embedding,\n121:         new_memory=memory,\n122:     )\n123: \n124:     logger.info(\n125:         \"memory-enriched processed\",\n126:         extra={\n127:             \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n128:             \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n129:             \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n130:             \"embedding_dim\": len(embedding),\n131:         },\n132:     )\n133: \n134: \n135: async def handle_memory_embedded(event: Event) -> None:\n136:     \"\"\"Process one ``Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED`` event.\n137: \n138:     Mirror of :func:`handle_memory_enriched` for the embed-finishes-\n139:     after-enrich ordering. Loads the memory row from storage (so we\n140:     have the embedding the minimal payload doesn't carry, plus\n141:     ``fleet_id``) and dispatches to :func:`detect_contradictions_async`\n142:     once the embedding has landed. Schema-drift / malformed payloads\n143:     ack-drop with a loud ``dropped=True`` log entry so a poison\n144:     message can't loop the subscription.\n145: \n146:     Like the enriched handler, the detection coroutine is awaited\n147:     inline rather than spawned via ``track_task``: it owns its own\n148:     ``try/except`` and never raises, so the bus always acks regardless\n149:     of detection outcome — but the await delays the ack until detection\n150:     completes, which prevents redelivery from stacking concurrent\n151:     detections on the same memory.\n152:     \"\"\"\n153:     try:\n154:         payload = MemoryEmbedded(**event.payload)\n155:     except (ValidationError, TypeError):\n156:         logger.exception(\n157:             \"dropping malformed memory-embedded payload\",\n158:             extra={\n159:                 \"event_type\": event.event_type,\n160:                 \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n161:                 \"dropped\": True,\n162:             },\n163:         )\n164:         return\n165: \n166:     sc = get_storage_client()\n167:     memory = await sc.get_memory(str(payload.memory_id))\n168:     if memory is None:\n169:         # Row was deleted between the worker's PATCH and our handler\n170:         # picking up the event. Common-enough race to ack-drop without\n171:         # noise; matches the worker's 404 handling.\n172:         logger.info(\n173:             \"memory-embedded: target row missing; ack-dropping\",\n174:             extra={\n175:                 \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n176:                 \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n177:             },\n178:         )\n179:         return\n180: \n181:     embedding = memory.get(\"embedding\")\n182:     if not embedding:\n183:         # Should not happen — the embed worker just PATCHed it before\n184:         # publishing — but guard against a soft-delete or column\n185:         # rewrite race rather than passing None into the detector.\n186:         logger.warning(\n187:             \"memory-embedded: embedding missing on read-back; ack-dropping\",\n188:             extra={\n189:                 \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n190:                 \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n191:             },\n192:         )\n193:         return\n194: \n195:     fleet_id = memory.get(\"fleet_id\")\n196: \n197:     await detect_contradictions_async(\n198:         payload.memory_id,\n199:         payload.tenant_id,\n200:         fleet_id,\n201:         payload.content,\n202:         embedding,\n203:         new_memory=memory,\n204:     )\n205: \n206:     logger.info(\n207:         \"memory-embedded processed\",\n208:         extra={\n209:             \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n210:             \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n211:             \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n212:             \"embedding_dim\": len(embedding),\n213:         },\n214:     )\n215: \n216: \n217: def register_consumers() -> None:\n218:     \"\"\"Wire the consumers into the event bus.\n219: \n220:     Must run before ``bus.start()`` — the Pub/Sub backend spawns its\n221:     pull loops in ``start()`` from the current handler registry, so a\n222:     late ``subscribe()`` would silently orphan the handler.\n223:     \"\"\"\n224:     bus = get_event_bus()\n225:     bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.ENRICHED, handle_memory_enriched)\n226:     bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED, handle_memory_embedded)\n\n(End of file - total 226 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Pub/Sub consumer for core-api.\n\nSubscribes core-api to two back-channels published by core-worker\nafter the async write path lands a memory row:\n\n* ``Topics.Memory.ENRICHED`` (CAURA-595) — fired after a successful\n  enrichment PATCH.\n* ``Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED`` (loadtest-7 fix) — fired after a\n  successful embedding PATCH.\n\nBoth consumers run :func:`detect_contradictions_async`. Two events\ntrigger the detector because either the embed or the enrich worker\ncan land first, and the detector needs both fields available; whichever\nevent arrives second sees the other side present and runs detection.\nThe detector is idempotent under repeated calls on the same row, so\nthe rare case where both events trigger detection back-to-back doesn't\ndouble-write contradiction rows.\n\nAtomic-fact fan-out (parent → child memories) is intentionally not\nhandled here. The worker drops ``EnrichmentResult.atomic_facts``","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py","text":"\"\"\"Pub/Sub consumer for core-api.\n\nSubscribes core-api to two back-channels published by core-worker\nafter the async write path lands a memory row:\n\n* ``Topics.Memory.ENRICHED`` (CAURA-595) — fired after a successful\n  enrichment PATCH.\n* ``Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED`` (loadtest-7 fix) — fired after a\n  successful embedding PATCH.\n\nBoth consumers run :func:`detect_contradictions_async`. Two events\ntrigger the detector because either the embed or the enrich worker\ncan land first, and the detector needs both fields available; whichever\nevent arrives second sees the other side present and runs detection.\nThe detector is idempotent under repeated calls on the same row, so\nthe rare case where both events trigger detection back-to-back doesn't\ndouble-write contradiction rows.\n\nAtomic-fact fan-out (parent → child memories) is intentionally not\nhandled here. The worker drops ``EnrichmentResult.atomic_facts``\nentirely (see ``_ENRICHMENT_UNROUTED_FIELDS`` in\n``core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py``), so they never reach\nstorage. Persisting them at the worker side and fanning out from a\nstorage fetch is a separate piece of work.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\n\nfrom pydantic import ValidationError\n\nfrom common.events.base import Event\nfrom common.events.factory import get_event_bus\nfrom common.events.memory_embedded import MemoryEmbedded\nfrom common.events.memory_enriched import MemoryEnriched\nfrom common.events.topics import Topics\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.services.contradiction_detector import detect_contradictions_async\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nasync def handle_memory_enriched(event: Event) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Process one ``Topics.Memory.ENRICHED`` event.\n\n    Loads the memory row from storage (so we have the embedding +\n    fleet_id that the minimal payload doesn't carry) and dispatches to\n    ``detect_contradictions_async`` when the embedding has already\n    landed. Schema-drift / malformed payloads ack-drop with a loud\n    ``dropped=True`` log entry so a poison message can't loop the\n    subscription.\n\n    The detection coroutine is awaited inline rather than spawned via\n    ``track_task``: it owns its own ``try/except`` and never raises, so\n    the bus always acks regardless of detection outcome — but the await\n    delays the ack until detection completes, which prevents\n    redelivery from stacking concurrent detections on the same memory.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        payload = MemoryEnriched(**event.payload)\n    except (ValidationError, TypeError):\n        # ``ValidationError`` covers shape drift (missing required\n        # fields, wrong types). ``TypeError`` covers ``event.payload``\n        # not being a mapping at all — ``**non_dict`` raises before\n        # Pydantic ever sees it. Both are poison-message conditions\n        # that re-raising would just nack-loop on; ack-drop loudly.\n        logger.exception(\n            \"dropping malformed memory-enriched payload\",\n            extra={\n                \"event_type\": event.event_type,\n                \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n                \"dropped\": True,\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    memory = await sc.get_memory(str(payload.memory_id))\n    if memory is None:\n        # Row was deleted between the worker's PATCH and our handler\n        # picking up the event. Common-enough race to ack-drop without\n        # noise; matches the worker's 404 handling.\n        logger.info(\n            \"memory-enriched: target row missing; ack-dropping\",\n            extra={\n                \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n                \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    embedding = memory.get(\"embedding\")\n    if not embedding:\n        # Embed worker hasn't completed yet (or its PATCH 404'd).\n        # ``deferred_reason`` is structured so a Cloud Logging metric\n        # can scrape the count of skipped detections — without it,\n        # there's no production visibility into how often the race\n        # fires.\n        logger.info(\n            \"memory-enriched: embedding not yet present; deferring contradiction detection\",\n            extra={\n                \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n                \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n                \"deferred_reason\": \"embedding_missing\",\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    fleet_id = memory.get(\"fleet_id\")\n\n    # Pass the already-fetched row through so the detector skips a\n    # redundant ``sc.get_memory`` (it still re-checks ``deleted_at``\n    # for the soft-delete-during-detection race).\n    await detect_contradictions_async(\n        payload.memory_id,\n        payload.tenant_id,\n        fleet_id,\n        payload.content,\n        embedding,\n        new_memory=memory,\n    )\n\n    logger.info(\n        \"memory-enriched processed\",\n        extra={\n            \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n            \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n            \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n            \"embedding_dim\": len(embedding),\n        },\n    )\n\n\nasync def handle_memory_embedded(event: Event) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Process one ``Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED`` event.\n\n    Mirror of :func:`handle_memory_enriched` for the embed-finishes-\n    after-enrich ordering. Loads the memory row from storage (so we\n    have the embedding the minimal payload doesn't carry, plus\n    ``fleet_id``) and dispatches to :func:`detect_contradictions_async`\n    once the embedding has landed. Schema-drift / malformed payloads\n    ack-drop with a loud ``dropped=True`` log entry so a poison\n    message can't loop the subscription.\n\n    Like the enriched handler, the detection coroutine is awaited\n    inline rather than spawned via ``track_task``: it owns its own\n    ``try/except`` and never raises, so the bus always acks regardless\n    of detection outcome — but the await delays the ack until detection\n    completes, which prevents redelivery from stacking concurrent\n    detections on the same memory.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        payload = MemoryEmbedded(**event.payload)\n    except (ValidationError, TypeError):\n        logger.exception(\n            \"dropping malformed memory-embedded payload\",\n            extra={\n                \"event_type\": event.event_type,\n                \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n                \"dropped\": True,\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    memory = await sc.get_memory(str(payload.memory_id))\n    if memory is None:\n        # Row was deleted between the worker's PATCH and our handler\n        # picking up the event. Common-enough race to ack-drop without\n        # noise; matches the worker's 404 handling.\n        logger.info(\n            \"memory-embedded: target row missing; ack-dropping\",\n            extra={\n                \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n                \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    embedding = memory.get(\"embedding\")\n    if not embedding:\n        # Should not happen — the embed worker just PATCHed it before\n        # publishing — but guard against a soft-delete or column\n        # rewrite race rather than passing None into the detector.\n        logger.warning(\n            \"memory-embedded: embedding missing on read-back; ack-dropping\",\n            extra={\n                \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n                \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    fleet_id = memory.get(\"fleet_id\")\n\n    await detect_contradictions_async(\n        payload.memory_id,\n        payload.tenant_id,\n        fleet_id,\n        payload.content,\n        embedding,\n        new_memory=memory,\n    )\n\n    logger.info(\n        \"memory-embedded processed\",\n        extra={\n            \"memory_id\": str(payload.memory_id),\n            \"tenant_id\": payload.tenant_id,\n            \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n            \"embedding_dim\": len(embedding),\n        },\n    )\n\n\ndef register_consumers() -> None:\n    \"\"\"Wire the consumers into the event bus.\n\n    Must run before ``bus.start()`` — the Pub/Sub backend spawns its\n    pull loops in ``start()`` from the current handler registry, so a\n    late ``subscribe()`` would silently orphan the handler.\n    \"\"\"\n    bus = get_event_bus()\n    bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.ENRICHED, handle_memory_enriched)\n    bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.EMBEDDED, handle_memory_embedded)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":226,"totalLines":226,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py","time":{"start":1780728175209,"end":1780728175213}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0317272579d6221c016a23c16eff7c8191a35ea40788f9a994"}},"id":"prt_e9bab9a15001tJgoOfq4XT1mR4","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","messageID":"msg_e9bab76bb001bokvLlWaHWPb4S"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728175306,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_HEqdZsg7cSJXniTGpFJU8BjI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/app.py","offset":385,"limit":25},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/app.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n385:         # they need to run:\n386:         #   * Archive + purge (CAURA-655 / -656) — SQL-only. Subscribed\n387:         #     by core-worker on SaaS; only registered here in OSS\n388:         #     standalone where there's no separate worker process.\n389:         #   * Crystallize + entity-link (CAURA-657) — pipeline-machinery\n390:         #     consumers. ALWAYS registered here because the pipeline\n391:         #     code lives in core-api and isn't reachable from worker.\n392:         from common.events.inprocess import InProcessEventBus\n393:         from common.events.lifecycle_handlers import (\n394:             register_archive_consumers,\n395:             register_pipeline_consumers,\n396:         )\n397:         from core_api.services.lifecycle_audit import make_storage_adapter\n398: \n399:         lifecycle_adapter = make_storage_adapter(get_storage_client())\n400:         register_pipeline_consumers(lifecycle_adapter)\n401:         if isinstance(event_bus, InProcessEventBus):\n402:             register_archive_consumers(lifecycle_adapter)\n403: \n404:         await event_bus.start()\n405: \n406:         yield\n407: \n408:         # Each shutdown step is independent — a failure in one (a\n409:         # bus pull-loop close that raises, a tracked task whose\n\n(Showing lines 385-409 of 671. Use offset=410 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"        # they need to run:\n        #   * Archive + purge (CAURA-655 / -656) — SQL-only. Subscribed\n        #     by core-worker on SaaS; only registered here in OSS\n        #     standalone where there's no separate worker process.\n        #   * Crystallize + entity-link (CAURA-657) — pipeline-machinery\n        #     consumers. ALWAYS registered here because the pipeline\n        #     code lives in core-api and isn't reachable from worker.\n        from common.events.inprocess import InProcessEventBus\n        from common.events.lifecycle_handlers import (\n            register_archive_consumers,\n            register_pipeline_consumers,\n        )\n        from core_api.services.lifecycle_audit import make_storage_adapter\n\n        lifecycle_adapter = make_storage_adapter(get_storage_client())\n        register_pipeline_consumers(lifecycle_adapter)\n        if isinstance(event_bus, InProcessEventBus):\n            register_archive_consumers(lifecycle_adapter)\n\n        await event_bus.start()","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/app.py","text":"        # they need to run:\n        #   * Archive + purge (CAURA-655 / -656) — SQL-only. Subscribed\n        #     by core-worker on SaaS; only registered here in OSS\n        #     standalone where there's no separate worker process.\n        #   * Crystallize + entity-link (CAURA-657) — pipeline-machinery\n        #     consumers. ALWAYS registered here because the pipeline\n        #     code lives in core-api and isn't reachable from worker.\n        from common.events.inprocess import InProcessEventBus\n        from common.events.lifecycle_handlers import (\n            register_archive_consumers,\n            register_pipeline_consumers,\n        )\n        from core_api.services.lifecycle_audit import make_storage_adapter\n\n        lifecycle_adapter = make_storage_adapter(get_storage_client())\n        register_pipeline_consumers(lifecycle_adapter)\n        if isinstance(event_bus, InProcessEventBus):\n            register_archive_consumers(lifecycle_adapter)\n\n        await event_bus.start()\n\n        yield\n\n        # Each shutdown step is independent — a failure in one (a\n        # bus pull-loop close that raises, a tracked task whose","lineStart":385,"lineEnd":409,"totalLines":671,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/app.py","time":{"start":1780728175300,"end":1780728175306}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0317272579d6221c016a23c16eff908191bc2d204c33b25fbe"}},"id":"prt_e9bab9a85001lHoBAcDmxyedl6","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","messageID":"msg_e9bab76bb001bokvLlWaHWPb4S"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728175366,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_sMAqeICmI19DtTex1u8YFokF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py","offset":176,"limit":40},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n176:     # Always-fire completion log (Gap 06): without this, \"function ran and\n177:     # found nothing\" is indistinguishable from \"function never fired\" — the\n178:     # exact failure mode that hid Gap 01 and Gap 04 for weeks. Memory id is\n179:     # in the message string itself (rather than ``extra``) so a plain\n180:     # ``grep path_a_completed <memory_id>`` works regardless of the\n181:     # structlog renderer's ``extra={}`` behaviour.\n182:     t_start = time.monotonic()\n183:     n_conflicts = 0\n184:     skipped = False\n185:     try:\n186:         # A4 #14 — back-channel idempotency. Both the ENRICHED and\n187:         # EMBEDDED handlers fire ``detect_contradictions_async`` for\n188:         # the same memory; whichever arrives first owns the lock and\n189:         # runs detection, the other skips. Fail-open: if Redis is\n190:         # unavailable, ``_acquire_path_a_lock`` returns True and we\n191:         # fall back to the prior double-detection behaviour (storage\n192:         # CAS still keeps writes idempotent).\n193:         if not await _acquire_path_a_lock(memory_id):\n194:             skipped = True\n195:             return\n196: \n197:         if new_memory is None:\n198:             sc = get_storage_client()\n199:             new_memory = await sc.get_memory(str(memory_id))\n200:         if not new_memory or new_memory.get(\"deleted_at\") is not None:\n201:             return\n202: \n203:         tenant_config = await resolve_config(None, tenant_id)\n204:         contradictions = await _detect(new_memory, embedding, tenant_config)\n205:         n_conflicts = len(contradictions) if contradictions else 0\n206: \n207:         if contradictions:\n208:             logger.info(\n209:                 \"Async contradiction detection found %d conflict(s) for memory %s\",\n210:                 len(contradictions),\n211:                 memory_id,\n212:             )\n213:     except Exception:\n214:         logger.exception(\"Async contradiction detection failed for memory %s\", memory_id)\n215:     finally:\n\n(Showing lines 176-215 of 1873. Use offset=216 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"    # Always-fire completion log (Gap 06): without this, \"function ran and\n    # found nothing\" is indistinguishable from \"function never fired\" — the\n    # exact failure mode that hid Gap 01 and Gap 04 for weeks. Memory id is\n    # in the message string itself (rather than ``extra``) so a plain\n    # ``grep path_a_completed <memory_id>`` works regardless of the\n    # structlog renderer's ``extra={}`` behaviour.\n    t_start = time.monotonic()\n    n_conflicts = 0\n    skipped = False\n    try:\n        # A4 #14 — back-channel idempotency. Both the ENRICHED and\n        # EMBEDDED handlers fire ``detect_contradictions_async`` for\n        # the same memory; whichever arrives first owns the lock and\n        # runs detection, the other skips. Fail-open: if Redis is\n        # unavailable, ``_acquire_path_a_lock`` returns True and we\n        # fall back to the prior double-detection behaviour (storage\n        # CAS still keeps writes idempotent).\n        if not await _acquire_path_a_lock(memory_id):\n            skipped = True\n            return","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py","text":"    # Always-fire completion log (Gap 06): without this, \"function ran and\n    # found nothing\" is indistinguishable from \"function never fired\" — the\n    # exact failure mode that hid Gap 01 and Gap 04 for weeks. Memory id is\n    # in the message string itself (rather than ``extra``) so a plain\n    # ``grep path_a_completed <memory_id>`` works regardless of the\n    # structlog renderer's ``extra={}`` behaviour.\n    t_start = time.monotonic()\n    n_conflicts = 0\n    skipped = False\n    try:\n        # A4 #14 — back-channel idempotency. Both the ENRICHED and\n        # EMBEDDED handlers fire ``detect_contradictions_async`` for\n        # the same memory; whichever arrives first owns the lock and\n        # runs detection, the other skips. Fail-open: if Redis is\n        # unavailable, ``_acquire_path_a_lock`` returns True and we\n        # fall back to the prior double-detection behaviour (storage\n        # CAS still keeps writes idempotent).\n        if not await _acquire_path_a_lock(memory_id):\n            skipped = True\n            return\n\n        if new_memory is None:\n            sc = get_storage_client()\n            new_memory = await sc.get_memory(str(memory_id))\n        if not new_memory or new_memory.get(\"deleted_at\") is not None:\n            return\n\n        tenant_config = await resolve_config(None, tenant_id)\n        contradictions = await _detect(new_memory, embedding, tenant_config)\n        n_conflicts = len(contradictions) if contradictions else 0\n\n        if contradictions:\n            logger.info(\n                \"Async contradiction detection found %d conflict(s) for memory %s\",\n                len(contradictions),\n                memory_id,\n            )\n    except Exception:\n        logger.exception(\"Async contradiction detection failed for memory %s\", memory_id)\n    finally:","lineStart":176,"lineEnd":215,"totalLines":1873,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py","time":{"start":1780728175361,"end":1780728175365}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0317272579d6221c016a23c16eff988191a5d5e88e6753def0"}},"id":"prt_e9bab9ad3001bPCa9Yf7e1nTCY","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","messageID":"msg_e9bab76bb001bokvLlWaHWPb4S"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780728175642,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab9c18001Rn50PXVGS1zpig","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"c1fff32e93f501fcb7fb59dc31626faac714f306","messageID":"msg_e9bab76bb001bokvLlWaHWPb4S","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":99590,"input":5058,"output":292,"reasoning":32,"cache":{"write":0,"read":94208}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780728178251,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"id":"prt_e9baba649001IFh9vsO2MuM37q","messageID":"msg_e9bab9d20001B3KEihbrgHpEz2","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","snapshot":"c6b3ad621f1ff1d8d97ef13845bed9055ff09939","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780728247757,"sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","part":{"id":"prt_e9babcf09001G0ylwDDjHqCaBE","messageID":"msg_e9bab9d20001B3KEihbrgHpEz2","sessionID":"ses_164567595ffekYKAW3lqY5njlC","type":"text","text":"## Mechanism\n\nWrite flow: `ParallelEmbedEnrich` decides whether embedding/enrichment run inline or defer. Fast mode always defers enrichment, and SaaS-style fast mode can defer embedding; deferred work is explicitly documented as later `EMBED_REQUESTED` / `ENRICH_REQUESTED` events consumed by `core-worker` and PATCHed back onto the row (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:7`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:16`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:26`). The hot write persists the memory first; if embedding is absent it stores `metadata.embedding_pending=true` (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/write_memory_row.py:36`). If fast-mode enrichment is absent it stores `metadata.enrichment_pending=true` (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/merge_enrichment_fields.py:65`).\n\nEmission: after the row exists, `ScheduleBackgroundTasks` publishes background embed/enrich work through service helpers rather than blocking the request (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/schedule_background_tasks.py:119`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/schedule_background_tasks.py:144`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/schedule_background_tasks.py:205`). `_schedule_embed_or_reembed` runs in-process retry in inline/local mode, but in deferred mode publishes `EMBED_REQUESTED` (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1544`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1561`). `_schedule_enrich_or_inline` similarly either runs in-process background enrichment or publishes `ENRICH_REQUESTED` (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1635`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1662`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1680`). The publishers validate payload schemas before transport, build an `Event`, and publish fire-and-forget (`common/events/memory_embed_publisher.py:21`, `common/events/memory_embed_publisher.py:30`, `common/events/memory_enrich_publisher.py:27`, `common/events/memory_enrich_publisher.py:50`).\n\nTransport model: the event envelope carries `event_id`, `event_type`, `tenant_id`, `correlation_id`, timestamp, and payload (`common/events/base.py:14`). `publish()` is explicitly fire-and-forget: it returns once accepted by the transport, not once every subscriber has processed it (`common/events/base.py:61`). `subscribe()` states Pub/Sub is at-least-once and handlers must be idempotent, using `event.event_id` as a natural dedup key when needed (`common/events/base.py:68`). The Pub/Sub implementation repeats that handlers must tolerate duplicate events because ack failures and handler exceptions cause redelivery (`common/events/pubsub.py:44`, `common/events/pubsub.py:49`). There is no application outbox in the inspected files; Pub/Sub provisioning, retry policies, and dead-letter topics are external infrastructure (`common/events/pubsub.py:7`).\n\nDelivery and failure behavior: Pub/Sub `publish()` queues to the SDK batch queue and deliberately does not wait on the returned future; shutdown drains in-flight batches, but per-message publish errors do not surface to callers (`common/events/pubsub.py:340`, `common/events/pubsub.py:348`). Subscriber loops pull messages, decode them, dispatch handlers, ack successful batches, and nack failed handler batches via `modify_ack_deadline(..., 0)` (`common/events/pubsub.py:513`, `common/events/pubsub.py:526`, `common/events/pubsub.py:535`, `common/events/pubsub.py:542`, `common/events/pubsub.py:548`). Malformed messages are ack-dropped to avoid infinite poison-message redelivery (`common/events/pubsub.py:621`). If any handler raises, `_dispatch_all` returns failure so Pub/Sub redelivers, and already-successful handlers must tolerate the duplicate (`common/events/pubsub.py:639`, `common/events/pubsub.py:646`, `common/events/pubsub.py:673`). Permanent subscription/config errors halt the pull loop and mark the bus unhealthy (`common/events/pubsub.py:563`, `common/events/pubsub.py:580`). The worker and API register subscribers before `bus.start()` because pull loops are created from the current registry (`core-worker/src/core_worker/app.py:90`, `core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py:217`).\n\nHandler idempotency: embed redelivery re-PATCHes the same embedding and uses content-hash cache to avoid re-calling the provider when possible (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:25`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:144`). Enrichment redelivery re-PATCHes fields and treats write-after-write as safe, while protecting agent-provided fields from being overwritten by worker defaults (`core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:473`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:368`). Lifecycle pipeline actions use an audit row plus a recent-success dedup window for LLM-heavy periodic work (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:133`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:157`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:314`). Back-channel contradiction detection is guarded by a lock/CAS pattern so both `EMBEDDED` and `ENRICHED` can fire without double-writing contradictions (`core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py:11`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:186`).\n\nStore/index consistency and reconciliation: MemClaw’s vector “index” is not a separate consumer-owned index in the inspected path; the worker PATCHes `embedding` back onto the canonical memory row and clears `metadata.embedding_pending=false` in the same PATCH (`core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:168`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:187`). Enrichment similarly clears `metadata.enrichment_pending=false` on successful worker PATCH (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:431`). Until embedding lands, search keeps rows visible through FTS fallback: rows without embeddings bypass vector similarity threshold if `has_embedding=False` (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/post_filter_results.py:21`). Reconciliation exists as a NULL-embedding scan that republishes the same `EMBED_REQUESTED` events; it is restart-idempotent because successfully patched rows stop matching `embedding IS NULL` (`core-worker/src/core_worker/backfill.py:1`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/backfill.py:22`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:237`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:249`). This is the strongest transferable consistency pattern: detect stale/missing derived state from canonical store columns, then feed repair through the same idempotent handler path.\n\n## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory (027/006)\n\n1. **Claim** · Treat embeddings/enrichment as derived state with explicit `pending`/`success` markers on the canonical row, not as implicit truth inferred from side effects. **Evidence** · MemClaw writes `embedding_pending=true` when storing without an embedding and clears it in the later PATCH (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/write_memory_row.py:36`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:187`); enrichment follows the same pending/clear pattern (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/merge_enrichment_fields.py:69`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:431`). **Maps-to** · 027/006. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Extra status fields can become stale unless reconciliation treats them as audit hints, not sole truth. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · A local SQLite store can persist `embedding_status`, `enrichment_status`, timestamps, and attempts cheaply; it does not need Pub/Sub, but it does need explicit derived-state visibility.\n\n2. **Claim** · Use one idempotent handler path for both first-time async work and repair/reconciliation. **Evidence** · MemClaw’s NULL-embedding backfill publishes the same `EMBED_REQUESTED` events used by normal deferred writes, and re-running naturally skips rows no longer NULL (`core-worker/src/core_worker/backfill.py:6`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/backfill.py:22`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/backfill.py:27`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:249`). **Maps-to** · 027/006. **Verdict** · ADOPT. **Risk** · If the handler has hidden non-idempotent side effects, repair can amplify damage. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · This maps directly to a local daemon/job table: scan missing vectors, enqueue the same embedding job, and let normal completion logic update the row.\n\n3. **Claim** · Preserve search availability during embedding lag by allowing lexical/FTS retrieval while vector state is pending. **Evidence** · MemClaw explicitly lets NULL-embedding rows pass via FTS and bypasses vector similarity threshold when `has_embedding=False` (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/post_filter_results.py:21`). **Maps-to** · 027/006 or retrieval child. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Recall/ranking quality is lower during pending windows, and UI/tool responses must expose partial-vector state honestly. **Confidence** · Medium-high. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit already has local BM25/FTS-style channels; it can keep rows visible immediately while vector work drains, without adopting fleet Pub/Sub.\n\n4. **Claim** · Define delivery semantics around idempotency, not exactly-once. **Evidence** · EventBus requires idempotent handlers under at-least-once delivery and recommends `event_id` for dedup (`common/events/base.py:73`); Pub/Sub dispatch nacks any handler failure, redelivering the event to all handlers (`common/events/pubsub.py:639`). Embed/enrich handlers are designed as safe write-after-write PATCHes (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:25`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:473`). **Maps-to** · 027/006. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Local in-process retries can still duplicate work unless job identity and derived-output writes are guarded. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit does not need distributed at-least-once transport, but it should still assume crashes/retries can replay jobs and make handlers deterministic or deduped by row id + content hash + target model.\n\n5. **Claim** · Completion/back-channel events are useful for downstream subscribers, but should be best-effort after canonical state is durable. **Evidence** · Worker publishes `EMBEDDED` and `ENRICHED` only after PATCH success, and publish failures are logged but do not nack the already-durable upstream PATCH (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:179`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:186`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:555`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:561`). Core-api consumes both because either embed or enrich can land first, and downstream detection is idempotent (`core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py:11`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet or 027/006 subscriber aid. **Verdict** · DEFER. **Risk** · In local Spec Kit, adding completion events before there are real subscribers creates machinery without value. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The principle transfers: “state first, notification second.” The event surface should wait until Spec Kit has concrete subscribers such as graph refresh, contradiction checks, or UI progress.\n\n## Negative knowledge\n\nDo not copy distributed Pub/Sub provisioning into Spec Kit Memory. MemClaw assumes externally managed topics/subscriptions, ack deadlines, retry policies, and dead-letter topics (`common/events/pubsub.py:7`). A local SQLite system should prefer an in-process queue or durable job table with retry counters and a reconciliation scan.\n\nDo not copy fire-and-forget publisher error blindness wholesale. MemClaw intentionally does not wait for Pub/Sub publish futures, accepting that per-message publish errors only land in SDK logs (`common/events/pubsub.py:340`, `common/events/pubsub.py:348`). In a local store, publish/enqueue should usually be in the same SQLite transaction as the row insert, or at least recorded durably before returning, because there is no managed broker to absorb the gap.\n\nDo not copy multi-tenant worker-pool complexity unless Spec Kit gains real multi-user daemon deployment. MemClaw’s per-tenant scoping, tenant config payloads, per-tenant storage slots, service-account tokens, and subscription prefixes solve fleet isolation problems (`common/events/factory.py:40`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:544`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/backfill.py:69`). Spec Kit should keep the pattern but collapse infrastructure to row/job identity and local locks.\n\nDo not copy back-channel event fanout before subscribers exist. MemClaw’s `EMBEDDED`/`ENRICHED` events exist because contradiction detection needs a post-PATCH trigger and can be idempotently invoked from either ordering (`core-api/src/core_api/consumer.py:11`). Spec Kit should first identify concrete local subscribers; otherwise, status columns plus reconciliation are enough.\n\nDo not treat lifecycle audit/dedup windows as a generic local requirement. MemClaw uses audit rows and 23-hour dedup windows for fleet cron actions (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:100`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:133`). Spec Kit may need job attempt history, but not fleet-cron dedup semantics unless it adds scheduled global lifecycle jobs.\n\n## Open questions\n\nIs there any storage-side trigger, SQL constraint, or API endpoint that atomically creates the memory row and records the deferred event/job? The inspected path suggests no application outbox.\n\nWhere are Pub/Sub retry and dead-letter policies provisioned, and what max-delivery-attempts are configured for embed/enrich topics?\n\nDoes MemClaw expose operator dashboards for rows stuck with `embedding_pending=true` or `enrichment_pending=true`, beyond the NULL-embedding backfill?\n\nAre enrichment-pending rows reconciled like NULL embeddings, or is only embedding repair implemented in this slice?\n\nHow often does FTS-only pending search produce user-visible quality regressions, and does MemClaw surface `has_embedding=false` to callers?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"088\",\"focus\":\"event-driven async pipeline + reconciliation/consistency\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.86,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: explicit pending/success derived-state columns for async enrichment and embedding\",\"ADOPT: reconciliation scans canonical missing derived state and reuses the same idempotent handler path\",\"ADAPT: keep lexical retrieval available while vector state is pending\"],\"sources\":[\"common/events/base.py:61\",\"common/events/base.py:73\",\"common/events/pubsub.py:340\",\"common/events/pubsub.py:639\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/write_memory_row.py:36\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/schedule_background_tasks.py:119\",\"core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:25\",\"core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:187\",\"core-worker/src/core_worker/backfill.py:22\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/post_filter_results.py:21\"]}","time":{"start":1780728188681,"end":1780728247752},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0bc6c6dad7d62da9016a23c17ca8d48191846056fee705f6e6","phase":"final_answer"}}}}
